<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-748-606  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 748 606.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 13 1990 v7 n32 p117(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Group to address computer users' rights. (Computer Professionalsfor Social Responsibility) (Business) (company profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Susan E.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Professionals for Social ResponsibilityComputer hackersElectronic Frontier FoundationGovernment Regulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Susan E. FisherandM;By allaying government fears and confusion over computer security, a group ofadvocates hopes to ensure the protection of computer users' civil rights.andM;The Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility (CPSR), a publicadvocacy group based in Palo Alto, Calif., will host during the next twoyears a series of roundtable discussions in Washington on civil-libertiesissues arising from the use of electronic media.andM;Eric Roberts, CPSR president, said a gap between technical experts and policymakers must be bridged.andP;  &quot;There is simply too much misinformation about howcomputer networks operate,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;This could produce terribly misguidedpublic policy.&quot;andM;Both lawmakers and computer users are struggling to fit computercommunications into existing legal and social frameworks.andP;  Swirling at thecenter of the controversy are some basic questions.andP;  Is digital informationand electronic speech protected by the First Amendment?andP;  Can the laws oftrespass be applied to those who tap into computer systems withoutauthorization?andM;Roberts said CPSR hopes to bring together lawmakers, computer users, FBIofficials, computer-industry representatives and computer-security expertsfor the meetings, and added that the group will also act as a watchdog overcomputer crime investigations and develop policy papers on civil libertiesand computers.andM;The project is being underwritten with a $275,000 grant from the ElectronicFrontier Foundation, which was founded by computer pioneer Mitch Kapor.andM;&quot;Good security in computer networks is not a technical problem, it's a socialproblem,&quot; said Kapor.andP;  &quot;It's wrong to put all the blame on the hackers.&quot;andM;Kapor points to the case of Craig Neidorf, a 20-year-old University ofMissouri student who was indicted on federal charges after he reproduced adocument from an electronic bulletin board into his electronic magazine.andO;Federal authorities said the document had been stolen, and Neidorf wastherefore guilty of transporting stolen property.andP;  Although the charges werelater dropped, the case raises some unresolved issues.andO;</TEXT></DOC>